    "body": "Introduce a new `MarkSet` autocommand that is called after a mark is set. Closes #27896.\r\n\r\nHere it is in action. My config looks like this:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"MarkSet\", {\r\n  desc = \"Print when a mark is set\",\r\n  callback = function(ev)\r\n    print(vim.inspect(ev))\r\n  end,\r\n})\r\n```\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/5f67230e-e5ba-477e-946b-4f75c6892365\r\n\r\nIf this PR is merged and there's interest, I'd also like to contribute a similar `MarkDeleted` autocommand.\r\n\r\nAssorted callouts:\r\n* `MarkSet` is not called for the funky marks like `\"`, `[`, `<`, etc. I'm happy to make it work for these cases though.\r\n* `mark.c` doesn't seem to have any direct unit tests. Is `test/functional/autocmd/` the best dir to add tests to?\r\n* I'd love if we could get additional data into the autocmd callback. In Lua, this can be done with the `data` param on `nvim_exec_autocmds`. Can we do a similar thing  with `apply_autocmds`? (It looks like no.) `apply_autocmds_group` does have a `data` param though; it powers both `apply_autocmds` and `nvim_exec_autocmds`.\r\n* I still need to add documentation.",
